3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"GMX calculates MKR/USDT funding rates using Chainlink price feeds and position imbalances within the GLP pool. Funding payments occur hourly based on the difference between perpetual and spot prices, with rates typically ranging from -0.1% to 0.1% per hour. Long positions pay funding when rates are positive, while shorts pay when negative. The oracle-based system reduces manipulation risks but creates dependency on external price feeds for accurate rate calculations."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","MKR","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MKR's governance-driven volatility creates frequent funding rate imbalances, especially around MakerDAO proposal votes and protocol upgrades. The token's mid-tier liquidity on GMX allows for meaningful arbitrage opportunities without excessive slippage. DeFi governance tokens like MKR often exhibit predictable funding cycles tied to protocol events, making them attractive for systematic funding rate strategies."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical MKR Funding Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MKR funding rates on GMX historically spike during major MakerDAO governance events, with rates reaching ±0.08% hourly during contentious votes. The token shows strong correlation with broader DeFi sentiment, often maintaining positive funding during DeFi bull runs and negative rates during bear markets. Quarterly governance cycles create predictable funding premium patterns, with increased activity typically leading to long bias and positive rates. Weekend funding tends to normalize due to reduced governance activity and lower institutional participation."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Strategies and Execution"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Cross-exchange arbitrage works effectively by shorting MKR perpetuals on GMX when funding is deeply negative while holding spot MKR or going long on centralized exchanges. The platform's 0.05%/0.07% trading fees require funding rate differentials above 0.12% to remain profitable after costs. Delta-neutral strategies benefit from GMX's isolated margin system, allowing precise position sizing without cross-margining risks. Timing entries around governance announcements can capture 2-4 hour funding premium periods before rates normalize."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Management Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Oracle dependency creates unique risks where Chainlink feed delays or anomalies can cause funding rate miscalculations, particularly during high volatility periods. GMX's GLP pool composition affects MKR liquidity, with lower allocations reducing available size for arbitrage positions. Smart contract risks include potential GLP pool drainage during extreme market conditions, which could impact position closure ability. Gas costs on Arbitrum, while low, can erode profits from small funding rate differences, requiring minimum position sizes around $10,000 for efficiency."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How does GMX's oracle pricing affect MKR funding accuracy?","answer":"GMX uses Chainlink oracles for MKR price discovery, which creates 1-2 second delays compared to spot markets. These delays can cause temporary funding rate distortions during rapid price movements, but generally provide more manipulation-resistant pricing than DEX-based feeds."},{"question":"What's the optimal position size for MKR funding arbitrage on GMX?","answer":"Minimum positions of $5,000-10,000 are recommended due to fixed gas costs and trading fees. Larger positions above $50,000 may face increased price impact, as MKR typically represents 1-3% of GMX's GLP pool allocation."},{"question":"How do MakerDAO governance events impact funding rates?","answer":"Major governance proposals often drive 24-48 hour periods of elevated funding rates, with executive votes creating stronger directional bias than simple polling. Emergency governance actions can cause extreme funding spikes exceeding ±0.15% hourly."},{"question":"Can funding payments be interrupted during GLP pool stress?","answer":"Funding continues during normal GLP operations, but extreme pool imbalances or utilization above 95% may trigger temporary trading halts. The protocol maintains reserve mechanisms to ensure funding payment continuity except during black swan events."}]}]
